"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576468","Department of Health","false","2016-09-13","<p>As set out in the NHS Shared Planning Guidance, published in December 2015, the success of Sustainability and Transformation Plans (STPs) will depend on having an open, engaging, and iterative process that harnesses the energies of clinicians, patients, carers, citizens, and local community partners including the independent and voluntary sectors and local government. The national bodies responsible for the development of the programme have continued to ask for robust local plans for genuine engagement as part of the STP process.</p><p> </p><p>STP proposals are currently at a draft stage, but it is expected that all local leaders will be talking to the public and stakeholders regularly as it is vital that people are able to shape the future of their local services. All local STP areas should therefore now be having conversations with local people and stakeholders – understanding what matters to them, and explaining how services might be improved. No changes to the services people currently receive will be made without local engagement, and if plans propose service changes that are agreed, then formal consultation will be followed in due course in line with good practice and legislative requirements. All footprints will submit an updated plan in October, with further formal public engagement and consultation taking place from this point, as appropriate. Many footprints are already publishing patient-facing summaries as part of their engagement programme.</p>","Warrington South","David Mowat",,"2016-09-13T15:40:41.027Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576468/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576468/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576468/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-09-05","NHS: Reorganisation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, whether Sustainability and Transformation plans will be (a) made public and (b) fully consulted on before being implemented.","false","Biography information for Mr Roger Godsiff","Birmingham, Hall Green","Mr Roger Godsiff","45067"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576469","Home Office","false","2016-09-12","<p>The Tier 4 visa pilot has been introduced to test the benefits of a differentiated approach within the education sector on the basis of compliance with immigration sponsorship requirements.</p><p>The pilot is deliberately narrow in scope, with institutions selected due to their consistently low visa refusal rates. This is to ensure that the outcomes can be adequately monitored, whilst minimising the risk of unintended consequences, before considering rolling-out the scheme more widely.</p><p>Should the pilot be successful, the Home Office will liaise with stakeholders, including Scottish universities, over plans for extending the scheme.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-09-12T16:18:40.69Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576469/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576469/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576469/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-09-05","Overseas Students: Scotland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, if she will make it her policy to include Scottish universities in the Government's tier 4 Visa Pilot.","false","Biography information for Natalie McGarry","Glasgow East","Natalie McGarry","45029"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576470","Home Office","false","2016-09-08","<p>All asylum claims are considered on their individual merits and based on the information provided throughout the process. Some decisions can be taken more quickly than others, for example if further information is needed to reach an informed decision it can take longer. If an asylum claim is refused then the claimant might appeal against that decision.</p><p>All straightforward claims are decided within 6 months.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-09-08T14:42:52.603Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576470/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576470/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576470/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-09-05","Asylum: Liverpool Wavertree","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what steps she is taking to reduce the application waiting times for people resident in Liverpool, Wavertree constituency who are seeking asylum.","false","Biography information for Luciana Berger","Liverpool, Wavertree","Luciana Berger","45017"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576471","Home Office","false","2016-09-08","<p>Data about the number of victims of human trafficking with mental health issues who receive support through the National Referral Mechanism (NRM) is not collated centrally. We work with victim support providers to strengthen data collection systems and will consider this as part of that.</p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton",,"2016-09-08T16:10:39.633Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576471/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576471/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576471/answer","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576471/answer/previousversion/9936","Biography information for Sarah Newton","1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-09-05","Human Trafficking: Females","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, with reference to the Answer of 11 April 2016 to Question 32631 on human trafficking: females, if she will take steps to ensure that data referred to is collected.","false","Biography information for Luciana Berger","Liverpool, Wavertree","Luciana Berger","45016"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576472","Home Office","false","2016-09-12","<p>For unaccompanied refugee children accepted for transfer to the UK, transfer requests are generally processed within 10 days and children transferred within weeks.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-09-12T12:37:11.203Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576472/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576472/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576472/answer","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576472/answer/previousversion/9937","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-09-05","Refugees: Children","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what the average time taken is for family reunification of unaccompanied refugee children in Europe.","false","Biography information for Mr Roger Godsiff","Birmingham, Hall Green","Mr Roger Godsiff","44965"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576473","Home Office","false","2016-09-08","<p>The Government recognises that policing can be a challenging job and it is the responsibility of chief officers – supported by the College of Policing - to ensure the welfare of all officers and staff. We welcome the work in forces, led nationally by Lancashire’s Deputy Chief Constable - to promote officer health and wellbeing. It is encouraging to see that all forces have signed up to the Workplace Wellbeing Charter.</p><p>As part of a commitment to police welfare in October 2014 the Government allocated £10m to help support emergency services personnel and volunteers, focused on mental health, physical recuperation and bereavement support for those who need it.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2016-09-08T14:38:39.8Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576473/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576473/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576473/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-09-05","Police: Lancashire","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what her plans are to tackle trends in stress-related illnesses among police officers in Lancashire.","false","Biography information for Mr Nigel Evans","Ribble Valley","Mr Nigel Evans","44962"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576474","Home Office","false","2016-09-08","<p>The latest quarterly Home Office immigration statistics on entry clearance visas are published in ‘Immigration Statistics, April - June 2016’, available from the Home Office website at:</p><p>https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/migration-statistics</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-09-08T14:43:17.18Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576474/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576474/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576474/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-09-05","Visas","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what number and proportion of (a) overall visa applications and (b) applications from Syrian passport holders have been rejected by her Department in the last year.","false","Biography information for Marion Fellows","Motherwell and Wishaw","Marion Fellows","45004"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576475","Home Office","false","2016-09-12","<p>For visa purposes, it is not Home Office policy to give an applicant the opportunity to submit a further document if they have provided an out of date English language certificate. Knowledge of the English language is a key requirement of the Immigration Rules which applicants are expected to comply with before they apply. The Immigration Rules specify that, where applicable, the test certificate must be within its validity date.</p><p>For naturalisation applications, a person is allowed a period of two weeks to provide any missing information, but they would be expected to have met the language requirement before submitting an application.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-09-12T16:19:04.063Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576475/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576475/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576475/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-09-05","Immigrants: English Language","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, if she will make it her policy to contact visa and naturalisation applicants to ask those applicants to submit an up-to-date English Language Certificate if an application is to be refused solely on the grounds of the submission of an expired certificate.","false","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson","44987"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576476","Home Office","false","2016-09-08","<p>There has been no assessment made of the enforcement by the police of the offence of driving whilst using a mobile phone. The enforcement of this offence is an operational matter for individual Chief Officers of police.</p><p>The attached table, “Fixed Penalty Notices” includes figures for Fixed Penalty Notices for use of mobile phones whilst driving, broken down by Police Force Area and by Year.</p><p>Based on information provided by the Ministry of Justice, statistics on offenders found guilty and sentenced, including sentence outcomes, for using or causing others to use a mobile phone whilst driving, at all courts in England and Wales, by police force area, from 2005 to 2015, can be viewed using the ‘Motoring data tool: with criminal justice area’ in the annual publication, linked below:- https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/criminal-justice-system-statistics-quarterly-december-2015</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis","44935","2016-09-08T10:36:19.44Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576476/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576476/answer","Copy of Fixed Penatly Notices v1.xls","Fixed Penalty Notices","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576476/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-09-05","Road Traffic Offences: Mobile Phones","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what statistics her Department holds on (a) convictions and (b) fines for mobile phone use while driving in each police force area.","false","Biography information for Stephen Hammond","Wimbledon","Stephen Hammond","44950"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576477","Department for Transport","false","2016-09-12","<p>In 2014, 1.6% of drivers in England and Scotland were observed using a mobile phone whilst driving. This is similar to the 1.4% of drivers observed using a hand held mobile phone in England in 2009, when the previous survey was carried out. In this context, we have recently consulted on proposals for increased penalties for this dangerous behaviour.</p><p> </p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-09-12T10:25:05.587Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576477/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576477/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576477/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-09-05","Road Traffic Offences: Mobile Phones","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what information his Department holds on trends in the incidence of mobile phone use while driving since it was prohibited.","false","Biography information for Stephen Hammond","Wimbledon","Stephen Hammond","44933"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576478","Home Office","false","2016-09-08","<p>There has been no assessment made of the enforcement by the police of the offence of driving whilst using a mobile phone. The enforcement of this offence is an operational matter for individual Chief Officers of police.</p><p>The attached table, “Fixed Penalty Notices” includes figures for Fixed Penalty Notices for use of mobile phones whilst driving, broken down by Police Force Area and by Year.</p><p>Based on information provided by the Ministry of Justice, statistics on offenders found guilty and sentenced, including sentence outcomes, for using or causing others to use a mobile phone whilst driving, at all courts in England and Wales, by police force area, from 2005 to 2015, can be viewed using the ‘Motoring data tool: with criminal justice area’ in the annual publication, linked below:- https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/criminal-justice-system-statistics-quarterly-december-2015</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis","44950","2016-09-08T10:36:19.487Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576478/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576478/answer","Copy of Fixed Penatly Notices v1.xls","Fixed Penalty Notices","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576478/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-09-05","Road Traffic Offences: Mobile Phones","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what assessment her Department has made of the (a) ability and (b) willingness of police forces to catch those using their mobile phone while driving.","false","Biography information for Stephen Hammond","Wimbledon","Stephen Hammond","44935"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576479","Home Office","false","2016-09-12","<p>The Department for Education’s consultation on Fire Safety Design for Schools – Building Bulletin (BB) 100 Revised closed on 15 August and the Department for Education is considering responses.</p><p>We will engage with the Department for Education on its proposals on the way forward, ahead of its publication .</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2016-09-12T12:39:34.937Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576479/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576479/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576479/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-09-05","Schools: Fire Extinguishers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what discussions her Department had with the Department for Education before the decision to withdraw government guidance that most new schools are expected to be fitted with automatic fire sprinkler systems.","false","Biography information for Jim Fitzpatrick","Poplar and Limehouse","Jim Fitzpatrick","44870"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576480","Department for Education","false","2016-09-20","<p>The UK has a long-established higher education system that supports, and therefore attracts, the brightest minds, at all stages of their careers. Existing rules on EU and other EEA students remain in force. Future arrangements for EU students wishing to study in the UK will need to be considered as part of wider discussions about the UK's relationship with the EU.</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2016-09-20T13:52:15.007Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576480/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576480/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576480/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-09-05","Overseas Students: Loans","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, if she will make it her policy to include students from other EU countries in the eligibility criteria for student loans in the 2017-18 and 2018-19 admissions years.","false","Biography information for Daniel Zeichner","Cambridge","Daniel Zeichner","44877"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576481","Home Office","false","2016-09-13","<p>International students are included in net migration statistics that are produced by the independent Office for National Statistics (ONS). In line with the internationally agreed UN definition, these statistics define a migrant as someone changing their normal place of residence for more than a year. Students are therefore included in the same way as other migrants. Other countries, such as the United States, Canada, and Australia also include students in their net migration figures.</p><p>Like other migrants, students who stay for longer than 12 months have an impact on communities, infrastructure and services while they are here, so it is right that they are included in the net migration count.</p><p>We are committed to reducing non-EU migration across all visa routes in order to bring net migration down to sustainable levels as soon as possible.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-09-13T14:36:03.637Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576481/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576481/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576481/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-09-05","Overseas Students","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, if she will make it her policy to remove international students from the Government's migration targets following the decision to leave the EU.","false","Biography information for Daniel Zeichner","Cambridge","Daniel Zeichner","44875"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576482","Home Office","false","2016-09-12","<p>The Prime Minister has been clear that she wants to protect the status of EU nationals already living and working in the UK, and the only circumstances in which that wouldn’t be possible is if British citizens’ rights in other EU Member States were not protected in return.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-09-12T16:19:23.127Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576482/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576482/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576482/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-09-05","EU Nationals: Universities","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, if she will make it her policy to ensure EU nationals currently employed in UK universities will retain their positions after the UK has left the EU.","false","Biography information for Daniel Zeichner","Cambridge","Daniel Zeichner","44880"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576483","Department for International Development","false","2016-09-12","<p>The Department for International Development offers a wide range of funding opportunities and grants for charities and not-for-profit organisations interested in delivering poverty reduction-related activities, including water and sanitation projects.</p><p>These include UK Aid Direct, which is an adaptive, demand-led, fund designed to support small and medium sized national and international Civil Society Organisations (CSOs) to reduce poverty through service delivery, livelihoods and security and justice; and the Global Innovation Fund which has been established to support innovators to develop, test and scale-up innovations with the potential to have transformational social impact on the millions of people living on less than $5 a day. A complete list of funding opportunities can be found on DFID’s website at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/international-development-funding" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/international-development-funding</a>.</p>","Stockton South","James Wharton",,"2016-09-12T15:14:08.637Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576483/answer","Biography information for James Wharton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576483/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576483/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-09-05","Developing Countries: Sanitation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what innovation start-up grants are available for charities that undertake water sanitation projects.","false","Biography information for Jess Phillips","Birmingham, Yardley","Jess Phillips","44869"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576484","Department for International Development","false","2016-09-08","<p>DFID employees living and working overseas may utilise up to 30 days annual leave, with exception of those at A band (Grade 7 and above) who are eligible for 31.5 days, plus agreed local public holidays.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2016-09-08T14:18:13.907Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576484/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576484/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576484/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-09-05","Department for International Development: Holiday Leave","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, how many days of holiday, on average, were awarded to departmental employees living and working overseas in 2015-16.","false","Biography information for Tim Farron","Westmorland and Lonsdale","Tim Farron","44957"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576485","Department for International Development","false","2016-09-12","<p>The UK has met the international commitment to spend 0.7% of gross national income on Official Development Assistance in recent years and we will continue to do so</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2016-09-12T15:03:10.437Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576485/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576485/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576485/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-09-05","Overseas Aid","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what progress her Department has made on meeting the target of committing 0.7 per cent of national income to international aid.","false","Biography information for David Simpson","Upper Bann","David Simpson","45066"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576486","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-09-08","<p>My department is looking at driving offences and penalties for those who kill or cause serious injury and the best way to take this work forward.</p>","North East Hertfordshire","Sir Oliver Heald",,"2016-09-08T15:06:31.477Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576486/answer","Biography information for Sir Oliver Heald","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576486/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576486/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-09-05","Dangerous Driving","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, when the Government intends to publish its consultation relating to death by dangerous driving and driving without due care and attention.","false","Biography information for Sir Charles Walker","Broxbourne","Mr Charles Walker","44964"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576487","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-09-08","<p>This information is available on gov.uk within the published Tribunals and Gender Recognition Statistics Quarterly.</p>","North East Hertfordshire","Sir Oliver Heald",,"2016-09-08T15:09:24.343Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576487/answer","Biography information for Sir Oliver Heald","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576487/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576487/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-09-05","Employment Tribunals Service: Fees and Charges","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what the average length of time was for fee remission in employment tribunal claims between receipt of such claims and final processing in the latest period for which figures are available; and what proportion of fee remission applications were successful in that period.","false","Biography information for Chris Stephens","Glasgow South West","Chris Stephens","44963"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576488","Department of Health","false","2016-09-08","<p>Department of Health guidance was published in 2011 on best practice to achieve urgent transfers within 14 days. NHS England continues to work with prison healthcare and secure mental health providers to improve processes so that this can be achieved.</p><p> </p><p>NHS England has provided information on transfers as detailed below.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Period</p></td><td><p>Transfers</p></td><td><p>Transfers &gt;14 days</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Quarter 1 Financial Year (FY) 2015-16</p></td><td><p>72</p></td><td><p>232</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Quarter 2 FY 2015-16</p></td><td><p>136</p></td><td><p>238</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Quarter 3 FY 2015-16</p></td><td><p>92</p></td><td><p>213</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Quarter 4 FY 2015-16</p></td><td><p>112</p></td><td><p>458</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Quarter 1 FY 2016-17</p></td><td><p>92</p></td><td><p>209</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p>Note: the numbers above are reported transfers in the time period, an individual prisoner may be represented in more than one time period</p><p> </p><p>Data for this indicator has improved since data collection began in April 2015. NHS England have since improved the data collection and quality under the Health and Justice Indicators of Performance and the information above now represents data from all prisons.</p><p> </p><p>NHS England intends to publish data collected through Health and Justice Indicators of Performance since April 2016 in future, but a firm date for publication is not yet available.</p>","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood",,"2016-09-08T16:54:11.35Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576488/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576488/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576488/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-09-05","Prisons: Mental Health Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what steps he is taking to ensure the efficient and timely transfer of prisoners to hospitals under the provisions of the Mental Health Act 1983; and how many prisoners have waited for more than 14 days for such a transfer in each quarter since April 2015.","false","Biography information for Luciana Berger","Liverpool, Wavertree","Luciana Berger","45018"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576489","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-09-08","<p>We have a big issue with prisons that are out of date and not fit for purpose, which makes it more difficult for our excellent governors and officers to manage them well. We have a £1.3 billion building programme. I want new modern prisons to be built in which prisoners will get the education and work they need to succeed in outside life and to close down some of our most dilapidated and out of date prisons. HM Prison Berwyn, a modern 2,106 place prison in Wrexham will open in 2017.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2016-09-08T16:57:29.91Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576489/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576489/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576489/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-09-05","Prisons","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what plans she has to open new prisons.","false","Biography information for Mr Peter Bone","Wellingborough","Mr Peter Bone","45032"
